observations.recommendation:
We recommended that, in case of negotiated procurement due to two failed biddings, the BAC should:
4. Ensure that the correct procedure is followed in negotiated procurements in accordance with the RIRR of Republic Act No. 9184;
5. Ensure that the specifications for the procurement of goods are based on relevant characteristics, functionality and/or performance by not allowing reference to brand names and models of the goods being processed for procurement;
6. Stop delegating negotiated procurements to the end-user except those under emergency cases; and
7. Conduct a mandatory review and evaluation of the terms, conditions, specifications, cost estimates in the procurement, if none or less than the required number of quotations or proposals are received, despite the extension of deadline for the third time. The review should be reflected in the RFQ through a duly signed stamp or other form of verifiable documentation.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
1. Require both the CICLC and the Accountant to reconcile the differences noted in the RPCPPE and the PPELC following the guidelines and procedures in COA Circular No. 2020-006 and effect necessary adjustments in the books to reflect the correct balance of PPE accounts;
2. Reassess the volume of work in the one-time cleansing of PPE and assign an adequate number of personnel needed to complete the procedures within three months or less in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006;
3. The GSO and the Accountant to maintain complete and updated PCs and PPELCs, respectively to have a reliable source of information on their recognized cost of the City’s PPE accounts;
4. The GSO and the Accountant reconcile the PCs and the PPELCs within 10 days after the rendition of the RPCPPE by the CICLC;
5. The GSO to speed up the collection of documents for donated land and furnish the Accountant with copies as basis for recording the transactions in the books;
6. The GSO to coordinate with the City Assessor to expedite the registration and/or transfer of titles of Land owned by, but not in the name of the City; and
7. The GSO coordinate with the Accountant and the Internal Audit Office to formulate amendments in the policies and procedures on record management to ensure that documents related to the purchase, donation, and transfer of ownership of land are complete and intact with copies served to all concerned offices.

We recommended that the Inventory Committee together with the City Accountant:
Exert extra effort to complete the conduct of physical count of the remaining PPE with total cost of ₱859,589,248.89 in compliance with existing rules and regulations;
Investigate the noted differences between the GL and the RPCPPE amounting to ₱136,987,793.60 and make necessary adjustments in the City’s books of accounts;
Make necessary adjustments in the City’s books of accounts for properties found during the physical count but were not recorded in the GL with total cost of ₱5,640,994.75;
Ensure that damaged, unusable, unserviceable and returned properties are reported in the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) and processed for disposal in accordance with existing rules and regulations;
Require the persons accountable for the lost properties with total cost of ₱86,480.00 to settle their accountabilities in accordance with existing rules and regulations; and
Make necessary adjustments to derecognize properties below the capitalization threshold in accordance with existing rules and regulations.
